Yes, I know. This newsletter is called Not Boring. But I=E2=80=99m going to=
 start this essay off by showing you the Most Boring Chart in All of Crypto=
=2E=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the 1 year price chart of USD Coin (=E2=80=9CUSDC=E2=80=9D),=
 the fiat-backed, fully-collateralized, dollar-denominated stablecoin issue=
d by Circle [https://substack.com/redirect/b7e2eca5-4083-4114-aa26-3f0d0fa1=
8c3b?u=3D16283549]. I dare you to find me a more boring chart.=C2=A0
For the entire past year, as prices of other crypto assets rollercoastered =
up and down and up and very down, USDC hugged the $1 line tightly. =F0=9F=
=A5=B1
For stablecoins, boring is good. Boring is the goal. And being the most bor=
ing stablecoin results in a chart that isn=E2=80=99t very boring at all:=C2=
=A0
That=E2=80=99s USDC=E2=80=99s market cap since its inception in October 201=
8, which represents the total USDC in circulation. At the time of writing, =
July 20th, 2022, that number stands at $54.8 billion. Circulating USDC has =
more than doubled in the past year, after growing 25x between July 2020 and=
 July 2021. Since its price is pegged to $1, increases in market cap mean t=
hat there=E2=80=99s more usage of USDC (the inverse is also true =E2=80=93 =
the market cap declines when people redeem their USDC for Dollars).
Boring is a feature, not a bug. It=E2=80=99s key to Circle=E2=80=99s first =
product value proposition =E2=80=93 digital dollars =E2=80=93 and it=E2=80=
=99s key to Circle=E2=80=99s mission: To raise global economic prosperity t=
hrough the frictionless exchange of financial value.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99ve heard of Circle, it=E2=80=99s likely because of USDC. Tha=
t=E2=80=99s the company=E2=80=99s first killer product. Recently, it announ=
ced that it=E2=80=99s launching a second, Euro Coin (EUROC).
But thinking about USDC and EUROC as just stablecoins misses the company=E2=
=80=99s ambitions to become:
The platform on top of which developers build a new financial system
The digital currency of choice institutional investors leverage for trading=
 and settlement
A tool that enables the frictionless, borderless exchange of value
It=E2=80=99s an ambitious bet in a competitive space, and one dogged by bot=
h valid and invalid concerns, many of which we=E2=80=99ll cover in this pie=
ce. Circle is trying to differentiate on trust, the necessary foundation fo=
r its ambitions. Increasingly, it seems to be working.
I didn=E2=80=99t give much thought to stablecoins until Luna=E2=80=99s UST =
blew up a couple of months ago. But as I=E2=80=99ve dug in, I=E2=80=99ve re=
alized that they=E2=80=99re one of the most solid use cases in web3 today, =
and a fundamental building block in the much bigger visions entrepreneurs i=
n the space are building towards. Once the idea of programmable, permission=
less money worms into your brain, it=E2=80=99s hard to see where stablecoin=
s wouldn=E2=80=99t provide an improvement over the status quo.=C2=A0
But let=E2=80=99s start with the basics and build up from there:=C2=A0
What are stablecoins?=C2=A0
How do stablecoin issuers generate revenue?=C2=A0
Why are stablecoins a valuable primitive?=C2=A0
How are USDC and Circle a platform?=C2=A0
What is Circle=E2=80=99s competitive advantage?=C2=A0
What would a new financial system built on Circle=E2=80=99s rails look like=
?=C2=A0
What Are Stablecoins?
If you=E2=80=99ve followed the crypto markets recently, you might=E2=80=99v=
e heard the word =E2=80=9Cstablecoin=E2=80=9D and chuckled. =E2=80=9CStable=
coin, huh?=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99d quip, =E2=80=9CNot very =E2=80=A6 stable =
=F0=9F=98=82.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a funny joke.=C2=A0
In May, UST (Terra=E2=80=99s stablecoin) lost its peg to the dollar (transl=
ation: it became worth less than $1). It flushed hard, bringing the entire =
Luna ecosystem down with it. Ultimately, it brought down crypto hedge fund =
Three Arrows Capital (=E2=80=9C3AC=E2=80=9D) which contributed to the downf=
all of Celsius, BlockFi, Voyager, and other Centralized Finance (=E2=80=9CC=
eFi=E2=80=9D) lenders. Friend of the newsletter Jon Wu [https://substack.co=
m/redirect/5a83ed11-c78c-4e51-986f-4c7db438c748?u=3D16283549] wrote a great=
 thread [https://substack.com/redirect/610d6f60-208c-4c6a-95fd-1093f6e28eec=
?u=3D16283549] / Not Boring essay [https://substack.com/redirect/27aa3296-9=
e76-49e2-91e9-7affe9f9292a?u=3D16283549] on Terra-Luna and UST, and Arthur =
Hayes [https://substack.com/redirect/2699b9c3-a750-4668-b0d9-2fe127eefe19?u=
=3D16283549] wrote the definitive piece on the 3AC collapse [https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/cd6e3f71-ee18-4a30-9726-d55785b4e5a4?u=3D16283549] in case =
you want to read more gory details.=C2=A0
The UST situation brought to light something that was apparent to anyone wh=
o dug into the math or simply walked through the logic: not all stablecoins=
 are created equal. Not all stablecoins are =E2=80=A6 stable.=C2=A0
The goal of a stablecoin is to stay pegged to its reference asset. For most=
 stablecoins, that=E2=80=99s the US Dollar. So one (1) USD stablecoin =E2=
=80=93 like USDC =E2=80=93 should be worth $1. As Alex Danco wrote in 2018 =
[https://substack.com/redirect/5bf2c64c-6260-4287-aa86-000061fa6623?u=3D162=
83549]:=C2=A0
The crucial test that any stablecoin must pass for the market to actually t=
rust it is: if a user wants to redeem their stablecoins for genuine dollars=
, under any reasonable circumstance, can they do so?
=E2=80=9CReasonable=E2=80=9D is doing a lot of work here. People should alw=
ays be able to redeem their stablecoins for genuine dollars. There are thre=
e main models stablecoin issuers pursue to make that happen:=C2=A0
Fiat-Backed
Cryptocurrency-Backed
Algorithmic
We=E2=80=99ll start last, first. Algorithmic stablecoins, like UST, aren=E2=
=80=99t backed by dollars, a basket of cryptos, commodities, or anything, r=
eally, outside of what they create themselves.=C2=A0
Instead of explaining this insanity myself, I=E2=80=99ll turn it over to th=
e inimitable Matt Levine [https://substack.com/redirect/927ea9bc-18bc-4178-=
a797-8ddc6f36d0cb?u=3D16283549]:
Here is how an algorithmic stablecoin works:
You wake up one morning and invent two crypto tokens.
One of them is the stablecoin, which I will call =E2=80=9CTerra,=E2=80=9D f=
or reasons that will become apparent.
The other one is not the stablecoin. I will call it =E2=80=9CLuna.=E2=80=9D
To be clear, they are both just things you made up, just numbers on a ledge=
r. (Probably the ledger is maintained on a decentralized blockchain, though=
 in theory you could do this on your computer in Excel.)=C2=A0
You try to find people to buy them.
Luna will trade at some price determined by supply and demand. If you make =
it up on your computer and keep the list in Excel and smirk when you tell p=
eople about this, that price will be zero, and none of this will work.
But if you do a good job of marketing Luna, that price will not be zero. If=
 the price is not zero then you=E2=80=99re in business.
You promise that people can always exchange one Terra for $1 worth of Luna.=
 If Luna trades at $0.10, then one Terra will get you 10 Luna. If Luna trad=
es at $20, then one Terra will get you 0.05 Luna. Doesn=E2=80=99t matter. T=
he price of Luna is arbitrary, but one Terra always gets you $1 worth of Lu=
na. (And vice versa: People can always exchange $1 worth of Luna for one Te=
rra.)
You set up an automated smart contract =E2=80=94 the =E2=80=9Calgorithm=E2=
=80=9D in =E2=80=9Calgorithmic stablecoin=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 to let people =
exchange their Terras for Lunas and Lunas for Terras.=C2=A0
Terra should trade at $1. If it trades above $1, people =E2=80=94 arbitrage=
urs =E2=80=94 can buy $1 worth of Luna for $1 and exchange them for one Ter=
ra worth more than a dollar, for an instant profit. If it trades below $1, =
people can buy one Terra for less than a dollar and exchange it for $1 wort=
h of Luna, for an instant profit. These arbitrage trades push the price of =
Terra back to $1 if it ever goes higher or lower.
The price of Luna will fluctuate. Over time, as trust in this ecosystem gro=
ws, it will probably mostly go up. But that is not essential to the stablec=
oin concept. As long as Luna robustly has a non-zero value, you can exchang=
e one Terra for some quantity of Luna that is worth $1, which means Terra s=
hould be worth $1, which means that its value should be stable.
=E2=80=9CAll of this is,=E2=80=9D Levine writes, =E2=80=9Cquite straightfor=
ward and correct, except for Point 7, which is insane.=E2=80=9D $UST and $L=
UNA rose in tandem, and they fell in tandem.=C2=A0
After UST=E2=80=99s collapse, the market for algorithmic stablecoins will l=
ikely be muted for a long time, so we don=E2=80=99t need to spend more time=
 here.=C2=A0
Cryptocurrency-backed stablecoins are backed by a basket of cryptocurrencie=
s and are typically overcollateralized, meaning that the dollar value of cr=
yptocurrencies in the reserve exceeds the dollar value of stablecoins outst=
anding. They achieve this by requiring each user to deposit more in another=
 token, like ETH or BTC, than they pull out in stablecoin.=C2=A0
The leading example here is MakerDAO=E2=80=99s stablecoin, DAI, with a $7.2=
 billion market cap.
Here=E2=80=99s how it works:=C2=A0
A user who wants to take out a loan opens a Vault by sending ERC-20 tokens =
like ETH, Wrapped BTC, and USDC to the smart contract and receives DAI in r=
eturn.=C2=A0
DAI borrowing is overcollateralized, meaning that you need to put in a high=
er dollar value in your ERC-20 token of choice than you take out in DAI, wi=
th higher collateral ratios depending on the volatility and liquidity of th=
e token you deposit. Currently, ETH has a minimum collateral ratio of 170%,=
 Wrapped BTC of 175%, and Staked ETH of 185%.=C2=A0
At any time, you can deposit your DAI back in and unlock the ERC-20 you=E2=
=80=99d locked up.=C2=A0
If, however, the price of your ERC-20 of choice drops to a point that break=
s the minimum collateral ratio, Maker will liquidate you, or sell your toke=
ns.=C2=A0
The disadvantage of borrowing DAI is that you need to put up a lot of colla=
teral =E2=80=93 currently, to borrow DAI with ETH requires a minimum collat=
eral ratio of 170%, meaning I=E2=80=99d need to put in at least $17,000 wor=
th of ETH to get 10,000 DAI. I also have to pay a Variable Annual Fee, curr=
ently at 0.50% for ETH deposits.=C2=A0
Plus, if the price of ETH drops to a point that breaks that ratio =E2=80=93=
 in this case, if it drops even one cent =E2=80=93 the smart contract liqui=
dates me by selling the ETH. That could mean that you might be forced to se=
ll at an inopportune time.
The advantage of DAI to the borrower is that it=E2=80=99s completely on-cha=
in, without the need for a centralized intermediary, and works well with yo=
ur existing crypto holdings. If you want to hold onto your ETH but take out=
 a little walking around money, you can just lock up the ETH, get DAI, and =
use it for any of the things you might use stablecoins for.=C2=A0
The advantage of DAI as a protocol is that, by being overcollateralized and=
 liquidating below certain thresholds, it can maintain stability and keep t=
he promise that users can redeem their DAI for their ERC-20 tokens in any r=
easonable scenario.=C2=A0
As a result, even during the recent turmoil, DAI has held up well. DAI=E2=
=80=99s chart isn=E2=80=99t quite as boring as USDC=E2=80=99s, but it=E2=80=
=99s pretty boring:=C2=A0
At the time of writing, it=E2=80=99s trading at around $1.00, as designed.=
=C2=A0
There are other crypto-backed stablecoins that are pegged to the dollar, wi=
th more launching regularly, others pegged to assets besides the US Dollar,=
 and others still that aren=E2=80=99t pegged to anything at all. Some just =
want to be reserve currencies themselves. OlympusDAO [https://substack.com/=
redirect/f2bb906e-f160-49af-949e-3c59b0d0df34?u=3D16283549], for example, h=
as a mix of tokens in its reserve, backing its =E2=80=9CFuture Decentralize=
d Reserve Currency,=E2=80=9D Ohm. If you=E2=80=99ve seen the (3,3) or (some=
thing, something) meme on Twitter, that comes from the game theory behind O=
hm, that it=E2=80=99s better for everyone if everyone just stakes their Ohm=
 and holds. Ohm has had a bumpy ride, falling from a peak of $420 to a curr=
ent price of $52.=C2=A0
There are other promising crypto reserve currency projects, all vying to bu=
ild an internet-native reserve that isn=E2=80=99t tied to the value of any =
fiat currency, but they=E2=80=99re different than stablecoins and outside t=
he scope of this piece.=C2=A0
That brings us to fiat-backed stablecoins, like USDC.=C2=A0
Circle=E2=80=99s USDC stablecoin is the most straightforward of the major s=
tablecoins: for every dollar of USDC in circulation, Circle holds $1 worth =
of straight cash and US Treasury Bills, for which there is the deepest and =
most liquid market of any asset in the world.
If you want to redeem 1 USDC for $1, no magic needs to happen. The dollar i=
s sitting there, either right in the USDC reserve bank accounts at BNY Mell=
on and other large banks, or invested in short-term Treasuries that are eas=
ier than anything else in the world to exchange into dollars. Circle posts =
weekly reporting and monthly attestations on its website [https://substack.=
com/redirect/85fb1612-203c-4dce-8636-48780aeaccc4?u=3D16283549].
To learn so much more about stablecoins, Circle, and USDC=E2=80=A6=20
